      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im thinking about ripping out a wall in my kitchen to make it more open but i have no idea if its a load bearing wall or not. how can i tell if i should leave it alone or if it's okay to move? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be cautious, but first, let us consider the structural integrity of your kitchen. If you were to rip out a wall, you would be removing a piece of the house's skeleton, and if that skeleton is made of a load-bearing wall, you might be trying to lift a heavy stone with your bare hands.\n\nYou must ask yourself: Is this wall a **load-bearing wall**? If it is, it supports the weight of the roof above. If you remove it, the roof will sag, and the house will collapse. If it is not a load-bearing wall, then it is just a partition, and you can safely move it.\n\nTo determine this, you need to find the **load-bearing wall markers**. These are usually painted on the wall with a red line or a specific symbol. If you see a red line, that is your load-bearing wall. If you do not see one, then it is likely a non-load-bearing wall.\n\nIf you are unsure, you can use a **load-bearing wall detector**. This is a tool that uses a magnet to detect the presence of steel reinforcement bars inside the wall. If the detector beeps, then the wall is load-bearing. If it does",
