    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to be skeptical, and honestly, if you don't see those red lines, you are likely looking at a **non-load-bearing wall**, but you can't just assume that just because you can't see the marker.\n\nThink about it like this: If you were building a house, you wouldn't put a load-bearing wall in the middle of a kitchen unless you had a reason to. If you were building a house, you wouldn't put a load-bearing wall in the middle of a kitchen unless you had a reason to.\n\nIf you are looking at the **attic**, you might see the floor joists. If you see the joists running *across* the wall, that means the wall is just a partition, and you can rip it out. If you see the joists running *along* the wall, that means the wall is holding up the roof, and you must leave it alone.\n\nIf you are looking at the **basement**, you might see the foundation beams. If you see the beams running *across* the wall, that means the wall is just a partition, and you can rip it out. If you see the beams running *along* the wall, that",
